s student years up to the works of his last decade, in which Italian lyricism is combined with great formal rigor. The author suggests that Dallapiccola should be understood not only as aninfluential figure in the post-war developments of Italian music, but also as one who renewed and revitalized the older traditions of Italian music. Raymond Fearn is Professor of Music at Keele University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aComposersvBiographyzItaly. 4aMusic. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aAntonio Machado.  aFormal Rigor.  aGoethe.  aHeine.  aHuman Voice.  aItalian Composer.  aItalian Lyricism.  aItalian Music.  aJames Joyce.  aLuigi Dallapiccola.  aOperas.  aPost-War Developments.  aSalvatore Quasimodo.  aTraditional Traditions.  aTwentieth Century.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781580466325?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781580466325423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781580466325/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles